# Definitions # {#definitions}

## ISO14083- and GLEC-Framework-related Definitions ## {#iso14083-definitions}
: <dfn>Actual Distance</dfn>
:: The actual route (with unit `kilometer`) taken for a consignment. [[!GLEC]] Framework. See also [[!ISO14083]] Section 3.1.27.1.

: <dfn>Consignment</dfn>
::
    Refers to a quantifiable quantity of cargo that can be distinctly
    identified as a single unit. It is transported from a sender or consignor to a
    receiver or consignee, irrespective of the mode of transportation employed. See [[!ISO14083]], Section 3.1.4.

: <dfn>Consignment id</dfn>
::
    A digital identifier which uniquely identifies a [=Consignment=] relative to the [=Host system=] and to the [=data recipient=].

: <dfn>Distance</dfn>
:: See [=Transport Distance=] and [=Actual Distance=]

: <dfn data-lt="Great Circle Distance|GCD">Great Circle Distance (GCD)</dfn>
::
    The shortest distance between two points by crow-line, including the curving of the Earth. It is an approach used in air transport. [[!GLEC]] Framework.

: <dfn data-noexport>Hub Activity</dfn>
:: The operations carried out at a hub, measured in the hub's throughput. [[!GLEC]] Framework.

: <dfn data-lt="Hub Operation Category|HOC">Hub Operation Category (HOC)</dfn>
:: Represents a grouping of hub operations sharing similar characteristics.  [[!GLEC]] Framework.

: <dfn data-noexport>Hub Operator</dfn>
:: Refers to the party that is offering hub services, including warehousing and transshipment services. See [[!ISO14083]], Section 3.1.13.

: <dfn>Primary Data</dfn>
::
    Data based on direct measurements of energy consumption. Also see [[!GLEC]] Framework.

: <dfn>Secondary Data</dfn>
::
    Any data that is not primary data. It applies to modeled and default data. [[!GLEC]] Framework.

: <dfn>Shipment</dfn>
::
    A shipment refers to the goods in a commercial transaction between a seller and a buyer.
    Refers to the consignments transported as part of this transaction via a transport
    chain from the consignor to the consignee. See [[!ISO14083]], Section 3.1.20.

: <dfn data-noexport>ShipmentFootprint</dfn>
:: See [[#dt-sf]] for the definition.

: <dfn>Shipment id</dfn>
::
    A digital identifier which uniquely identifies a [=Shipment=] relative to the [=Host system=] and to the [=Data recipient=].

: <dfn>Shipper</dfn>
:: Refers to the party sending goods for transport; e.g. buying transport services from [=Transport Service Organizers=] or [=Transport Operators=]. See [[!GLEC]] Framework.

: <dfn>Shortest Feasible Distance</dfn> (SFD)
::
    Represents the shortest practical route between two places taking into account the real operating conditions. [[!GLEC]] Framework.

: <dfn>Transport Activity</dfn>
::
    Transport activity for each consignment is calculated by multiplying the consignment's mass by the TCE distance.
    It is measured with unit `tonne-kilometer`. See [[!ISO14083]] Section 3.1.24 and the [[!GLEC]] Framework.

: <dfn data-lt="Transport Chain|TC">Transport Chain (TC)</dfn>
:: A Transport Chain as defined in the [[!GLEC]] Framework. A TC consists of 1 or more [=Transport Chain Elements=]. A TC corresponds to a shipment.

: <dfn data-lt="Transport Chain Element">Transport Chain Element (TCE)</dfn>
:: Represents one element of the transport chain. It can consist of a transport activity or a hub activity. [[!GLEC]] Framework.

: <dfn>Transport Distance</dfn>
:: Refers to the distance covered from the consignor to the consignee during the transportation of the freight. [[!GLEC]] Framework. See also [[!ISO14083]] 3.1.27.

: <dfn data-lt="Transport Operation Category|TOC" id='toc-dfn'>Transport Operation Category (TOC)</dfn>
:: Represents a grouping of transport services sharing similar characteristics.  [[!GLEC]] Framework.

: <dfn>Transport Operator</dfn>
:: Refers to the party that carries out the transport service. See [[!ISO14083]], Section 3.1.30.

: <dfn>Transport Service Organizer</dfn>
:: Refers to the party providing transport services, where some of the operations are subcontracted to a third party, usually a Transport Operator. See [[!ISO14083]], Section 3.1.32.

: <dfn>Transport Service User</dfn>
:: Refers to the party that purchases and/or utilizes a transport service. It could be a [=shipper=] or a [=Transport Service Organizer=]. See [[!ISO14083]], Section 3.1.33.

: <dfn>Tool Provider</dfn>
::
    Provider of software, tools, services, or programs that support companies in
    calculating and reporting logistics GHG emissions conforming to these technical specifications.


## Auxiliary Definitions ## {#auxiliary-definitions}

Issue: Needs revision

: <dfn>Access Token</dfn>
:: Credential to provide access to protected resources, as defined in [[!rfc6749]] Section 1.4 (see also Section 5.1 and Appendix A.12).

: <dfn>Data Owner</dfn>
:: The party in the logistics value chain that owns the data being exchanged.

: <dfn>Data Recipient</dfn>
:: The party in the logistics value chain requesting and/or receiving the data being exchanged.

: <dfn>Host System</dfn>
:: A host system serves the needs of a single or multiple [=data owner=].
    Additionally, it can also serve the needs of a [=data recipient=], by calling the HTTP REST API defined in [[#http-rest-api]].
    A host system implements support for the data transactions defined in [[#txns]].

: <dfn>iLEAP standalone protocol</dfn>
::
    The [=iLEAP standalone API=] and [[#data-model|data model]], introduced in v1.1.0 of these technical specifications, which enables the exchange
    of logistics emissions. See [[#http-rest-api]] for details.

: <dfn>OpenId Provider Configuration Document</dfn>
:: An OpenId Provider Configuration Document in accordance with [[!OPENID-CONNECT]] section 4.

: <dfn>PCF</dfn>
::
    Product Carbon Footprint. See [PACT Technical Specifications](https://wbcsd.github.io/tr/2023/data-exchange-protocol-20231207/#dt-carbonfootprint) for further details.

: <dfn data-lt="Smart Freight Center|SFC" data-noexport>Smart Freight Centre (SFC)</dfn>
:: The [Smart Freight Centre](https://www.smartfreightcentre.org) Organization.

# Business Cases # {#business-cases}

Note: Non-normative section

These specifications shall serve the general need of businesses for logistics GHG emissions
accounting and reporting, conforming to the [[!GLEC]] Framework and [[!ISO14083]].

Given the nature of the logistics industry, and in order to reduce costs overall, these specifications aim at
enabling interoperability in the exchange of emissions data between different parties in the logistics value chain.

To achieve this objective, the specifications are guided by a set of business cases which provide the
framework for delineating subsequent [[#txns|data transactions]] and the [[#data-model|iLEAP data model]].


## Quantification of (Avoided) Emissions ## {#business-case-1}

A [=Transport Service User=] requests its [=Transport Service Organizers=] or [=Transport Operators=] to provide it with the GHG emissions of [=Shipments=].
The transport service user is interested in accessing accurate emission and emission intensity values based on actual measurements ("primary data").

Accurate logistics emissions values also enable the Transport Service User to compare logistics emissions and the resulting reductions from operational measures.

Data Transactions 1 ([[#txn1]]) and 2 ([[#txn2]]) enable this business case.

## Procurement of Carbon-Efficient Logistics Services ## {#business-case-2}

A [=Transport Service Organizer=] requests their [=Transport Operators=] to share GHG emission intensity information at the [=TOC=] or [=HOC=] level.
Similarly, a [=Transport Service User=] requests intensity information from its [=Transport Service Organizers=] and [=Transport Operators=].

By incorporating emission intensities in procurement processes, the parties are enabled to select services by carbon-efficiency advantages.

Data Transaction 2 [[#txn2]] enable this business case.

## Emissions Calculation from Transport Activity Data ## {#business-case-3}

Consider the two following scenarios:
    - A [=Transport Operator=], and possibly also [=Transport Service Organizer=], is not yet able to calculate GHG
        emissions according to the [[!GLEC|GLEC Framework]] and [[!ISO14083]].
    - A stakeholder collects primary data related to transport
        activity but is not in the business of calculating emissions data.

In each case, the party can collect [=Transport Activity Data=], that is, data related to a
single shipment including mass, distance, and energy carriers used, but excluding emissions data.

After collecting Transport Activity Data, the party can calculate TOC and HOC level data from its
Transport Activity Data, either inhouse or by contracting a third party (such as a [=Tool Provider=]).

This business case is particularly relevant for SMEs to reduce the entry barrier for logistics
emissions reporting.

iLEAP generally simplifies data collection efforts for the parties involved in this business case.
For instance, each party needs to collect the activity data only once. This data can be then made
available to multiple parties for different purposes, including business cases beyond emissions
calculations.

Data Transaction 3 ([[#txn3]]) enables this business case.


## Aggregated Emissions Reporting ## {#business-case-4}

Consider the following scenarios:

1. A [=Transport Service Organizer=] or a [=Transport Service User=] requests emissions data
    from a [=Transport Operator=] or a [=Transport Service Organizer=] which decide to share
    an [[#dt-ar|aggregated report]] instead of [[#txn1|TCE-level data]], due to privacy or competition concerns.
1. A [=Transport Service User=] or a [=Transport Service Organizer=] requests emissions reports from
    a [=Transport Operator=] or a [=Transport Service Organizer=], aggregated
    per transport mode or over one or more shipments.
1. A [=Transport Service User=], a [=Transport Service Organizer=], or a [=Transport Operator=] needs to
    report logistics emissions data to a public body for regulatory purposes.

Data Transaction 4 ([[#txn4]]) enables this business case, while Data Transactions 1, 2, and 3
support the collection of relevant input data for report calculations (see [[#txn1]], [[#txn2]], [[#txn3]]).


## Additional Business Cases ## {#txns-appendix}


: Disclosure of Logistics Emissions as part of PCFs
::
    A [=Transport Service User=] is requested to disclose logistics emissions as part of a [=PCF=].
    A Transport Service User can disclose this data as a data model extension (see [[#pcf-mapping-sf]]).

    This is enabled through the usage of the [PACT Technical Specifications](https://wbcsd.github.io/tr/2023/data-exchange-protocol-20231207/#api-error-responses)
    and disclosing through so-called Data Model Extensions based on the iLEAP
    Data Model ([[#data-model]]). See the PACT [[!DATA-MODEL-EXTENSIONS]] specifications.


: Forecasting
:: A [=Transport Service User=] requests their service provider ([=Transport Service Organizer=] or [=Transport Operator=]) to share GHG emissions at the TOC or HOC level. This enables the Transport Service User to forecast emissions related to specific activities or services, before these take place.



# Data Transactions # {#txns}

Note: Non-normative section

A data transaction is an abstraction for the exchange of data between two parties, serving one or more business cases ([[#business-cases]]).

It facilitates interoperability between different parties by explaining the context and their intentions.

Each transaction enables interoperability between [=host systems=] by exchanging data in the format
defined by the iLEAP data model ([[#data-model]]) through the protocols defined in
[[#http-rest-api]] and the PACT Data Exchange Protocol ([[#pcf-mapping]]).

The following diagram shows how data transactions 1, 2, and 3 are related:

Issue: A new diagram reflecting Data Transaction 4 is needed.

<figure id="figure-data-transactions">
  <img src="diagrams/transactions.svg" width="90%" >
  <figcaption>Transactions diagram</figcaption>
</figure>

Note: A [=Tool Provider=] can assume various roles on behalf of the [=Transport Service User=], [=Transport Service Organizer=], or [=Transport Operator=]. They can serve as mediators in activities involving data collection, calculation, and reporting.

## Data Transaction 1: TCE Data Exchange ## {#txn1}

This data transaction enables a [=Transport Service User=] (for example, a [=shipper=]) to receive emissions from [=Transport Chain Elements=] from a
[=Transport Operator=] or a [=Transport Service Organizer=] for a single [=shipment=].

To execute this transaction, the [=Transport Operator=] or the [=Transport Service Organizer=] MUST

1. calculate the emissions of 1 or more [=Transport Chain Elements=] in accordance with the [[!GLEC]] Framework and [[!ISO14083]], and then
2. make the resulting <{ShipmentFootprint}> available to the [=Transport Service User=]
    through the (recommended) [=iLEAP standalone protocol=] ([[#action-sd]]) and through the (deprecated) PACT Data Exchange Protocol ([[#pcf-mapping-sf]]).

The [=Transport Service User=] CAN then derive emissions using the [=shipment id=], by
1. collecting the <{TCE|TCEs}> from the <{ShipmentFootprint|ShipmentFootprints}> of all the [=Transport Operators=] and the [=Transport Service Organizers=] involved in the shipment;
2. forming the [=TC=] from the collected TCEs;
3. calculating the logistics emissions of the shipment in accordance with the [[!GLEC]] Framework and [[!ISO14083]].

Note: For an example exchange, see [[#example]].


## Data Transaction 2: TOC or HOC Data Exchange ## {#txn2}

This data transaction enables a [=Transport Service Organizer=] or a [=Transport Service User=] to receive [=TOC=] or [=HOC=] emission intensity data from a [=Transport Operator=].

The provision of emission intensity data at the [=TOC=] or [=HOC=] level enables the [=Transport Service Organizer=] or [=Transport Service User=] to collect the necessary information to calculate emissions according to the GLEC Framework and [[!ISO14083]].
It also facilitates the inclusion of emission intensity in procurement processes, allowing for the provision of services that offer carbon-efficiency advantages (see Business Case 2).

To execute this transaction, first the [=Transport Operator=] or [=Transport Service Organizer=] MUST

1. calculate 1 or more TOC or HOC emission profiles in accordance with the [[!GLEC]] Framework and [[!ISO14083]], and then
2. make the resulting <{TOC|TOCs}> or <{HOC|HOCs}> available through the [=iLEAP standalone protocol=] ([[#action-tocd]] and
    [[#action-hocd]]) and through the PACT Data Exchange Protocol (see [[#pcf-mapping]]).

    Note: Details on the definition and calculation of [=TOCs=] and [=HOCs=] are specified in [[!ISO14083]]
    and guidance is provided in the [[!GLEC]] Framework.

Then, a [=Transport Service Organizer=] or a [=Transport Service User=] can
retrieve the <{TOC|TOCs}> or <{HOC|HOCs}> using the (recommended)
[=iLEAP standalone protocol=] ([[#action-tocd]] and [[#action-hocd]])
or the (deprecated) PACT Data Exchange Protocol ([[#pcf-mapping-sf]]).
(see [[#pcf-mapping]] for details).


## Data Transaction 3: Transport Activity Data Exchange ## {#txn3}

Note:
      This data transaction is considered necessary by logistics parties, especially SMEs,
      lacking the capabilities to make emissions data available. Yet, standardizing the
      exchange of activity data can enable the use of primary data and facilitate the calculation of emissions data.

This data transaction enables a [=Transport Service Organizer=] or a [=Transport Service User=] to
receive [=Transport Activity Data=] from a [=Transport Operator=], as described in Business Case 3 ([[#business-case-3]]).

Using Data Transaction 3 is recommended for the following cases:

1. emissions data (at the level of <{ShipmentFootprint|ShipmentFootprints}>,
    <{TOC|TOCs}>, or <{HOC|HOCs}>) is not (yet) available, or
2. the data flow is used to calculate emissions data, e.g. by a [=Tool Provider=] on behalf of a [=Transport Service Organizer=] or a [=Transport Operator=].

To enable this transaction, the data owner (a [=Transport Operator=] or [=Transport Service Organizer=]) must

1. collect Transport Activity Data scoped by a single consignment, and then
2. make the resulting <{TAD}> available through [[#action-tad]].

Then, the [=Transport Service Organizer=] or [=Transport Service User=] can retrieve
the <{TAD|TADs}> through the [=ileap standalone protocol=] using [[#action-tad]]).


## Data Transaction 4: Aggregated Emissions Data Exchange ## {#txn4}

This data transaction enables a [=Transport Service Organizer=], a [=Transport Service User=], or
Public Authorities to receive emissions data related to one or more shipments from a [=Transport
Operator=], a [=Transport Service Organizer=], or a [=Transport Service User=], without disclosing
TCE-level data. The data exchanged through this transaction MAY disclose emissions aggregated per
transport mode and an aggregation of all hub <{TCE|TCEs}> (as requested in [[!ISO14083]] Chapter 13.3.2, see
information"j)").

To execute this transaction, a [=Transport Operator=] or [=Transport Service Organizer=] MUST:

1. calculate all <{TCE|TCEs}>' emissions corresponding to the shipment(s) in accordance with the GLEC Framework and ISO 14083,
2. generate the <{AR|AggregatedReport}> from the collected <{TCE|TCEs}>, and
3. make the <{AR|AggregatedReport}> available to a [=Transport Service Organizer=], [=Transport Service
    User=], or Public Body, through an iLEAP Conformant API.

Advisement: Aggregated Emissions Data is less granular than TCE-level data. Therefore, once
Aggregated Emissions Data is exchanged, it is no longer possible to derive more granular (i.e.,
TCE-level) data from it, thereby affecting the all data exchanges downstream. Please consider this
when opting for this data transaction.

### Examples ### {#txn4-examples}

Note: The following are are usecase examples, where a Transport Service Organizer and a Telematics
Provider send data to a GHG Calculation Tool with the goal of having the emissions calculated and
aggregated, in order to share less granular data with a Transport Service User.

