# HTTP REST API # {#http-rest-api}

## Introduction ## {#http-rest-api-introduction}

The iLEAP Technical Specifications define two REST API families:

: <dfn>iLEAP standalone API</dfn>
::
    The standalone API enables the exchange of <{ShipmentFootprint}>, <{TOC}>, <{HOC}>, <{TAD|Transport Activity Data}>, and
    <{AggregatedReport|Aggregated Report}> data.

    The standalone API consists of the following REQUIRED actions:
      1. [[#action-authenticate]] and the authentication flow [[#authentication]]
      1. [[#action-sd]] for the exchange of <{ShipmentFootprint|ShipmentFootprints}>
      1. [[#action-tocd]] for the exchange of <{TOC|TOCs}>
      1. [[#action-hocd]] for the exchange of <{HOC|HOCs}>
      1. [[#action-tad]] for the exchange of <{TAD}>
      1. [[#action-aed]] for the exchange of <{AR|Aggregated Reports}>

    Except for [[#action-authenticate|Action Authenticate]], all actions share characteristics
    regarding [[#access-control|access control]], [[#filtering|filtering]], and [[#pagination|pagination]] of results,
    as well as the request and response syntax.

    A [=host system=] MUST implement the [=iLEAP standalone API=] which is now the preferred option for data exchange.

    Note: The [=iLEAP standalone API=] is introduced in v1.1.0. It is RECOMENDED for [=data recipients=].

: <dfn>PACT-based API</dfn>
::
    The PACT-based API also enables the exchange of <{ShipmentFootprint}>, <{TOC}>, and <{HOC}> data, yet
    is based on the [[!PACTDX]] Protocol (see [[#pcf-mapping]]).

    The PACT-based API is enabled through a mapping from the iLEAP Data model
    to the [[!PACTDX|PACT PCF data model]] (see [[#pcf-mapping]]). The exchange
    of mapped data through the PACT-based API is done through the actions
    defined in [[!PACTDX]] chapters 7.6 and 7.7, plus the authentication
    flow defined in [[!PACTDX]] chapter 6.3.

    Since April 1 2026, the v2 family of the PACT Technical Specifications, including [[PACTDX]],
    is sunset. Consequently, the [=PACT-based API=] approach SHOULD only
    be used for backward compatibility reasons.


Advisement: We recommend new implementations to use the [=iLEAP standalone API=] by default.
Specifically, we encourage data recipients to pull data through the new endpoints.
Accordingly, data owners are encouraged to prioritize the implementation of the new endpoints, which is required for
conformance with iLEAP v1.1.0.



<figure id="api-endpoint-mapping">
  <table class="data">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>PACT-based API
        <th>iLEAP standalone API
        <th>Notes
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>`POST` [=AuthEndpoint=] or `/auth/token`
        <td>`POST` [=AuthEndpoint=] or `/auth/token`
        <td>Authentication flow kept
      <tr>
        <td rowspan="3">`GET` `/2/footprints`
        <td>`GET` `/v1/ileap/shipments`
        <td rowspan="3"> <{ShipmentFootprint}>, <{TOC}>, and <{HOC}> now have separate endpoints
      <tr>
        <td>`GET` `/v1/ileap/tocs`
      <tr>
        <td>`GET` `/v1/ileap/hocs`
      <tr>
        <td rowspan="3">`GET` `/2/footprints/$GetPfId$`
        <td>`GET` `/v1/ileap/shipments?shipmentId=$shipmentId$`
        <td rowspan="3">Requesting one single <{ShipmentFootprint}>, <{TOC}>, or <{HOC}> is now done by filtering on the respective identifier
      <tr>
        <td>`GET` `/v1/ileap/tocs?tocId=$tocId$`
      <tr>
        <td>`GET` `/v1/ileap/hocs?hocId=$hocId$`
      <tr>
        <td>
        <td>`GET` `/v1/ileap/tad`
        <td>New endpoint for the exchange of <{TAD|Transport Activity Data}> (previously `/2/ileap/tad`)
      <tr>
        <td>
        <td>`GET` `/v1/ileap/aed`
        <td>New endpoint for the exchange of <{AR|Aggregated Reports}>
  </table>
<figcaption>Mapping PACT-based to iLEAP native endpoints</figcaption>
</figure>


## Definitions and Parameters ## {#definitions-and-parameters}

The following defintions and parameters are used throughout this chapter:

: <dfn>Subpath</dfn>
:: If a host system uses a relative subpath, then the requesting data recipient MUST prepend this subpath.

: <dfn>Hostname</dfn>
:: The requesting data recipient MUST use the domain name of the host system.

: <dfn>BearerToken</dfn>
:: See [[!PACTDX]] section 7.3 Authentication Flow or [[#authentication]].

: <dfn>Filter</dfn>
::
    `Filter` is an OPTIONAL request parameter containing a filter statement.
    A <dfn>filter statement</dfn> is a list of name-value filter pairs.
    Each filter pair has a `$name=$value` syntax where `$name` is the (case-sensitive) name
    of the field to filter by, and `$value` the (case-insensitive) value to filter for.
    Filter pairs CAN be concatenated with `&`.

    The `$name` of a filter pair CAN use dot notation to reference nested or embedded
    properties within a data type. When dot notation is used:

    1. Each segment of the path (separated by `.`) represents a property name;
    2. For properties that are arrays (e.g., <{ShipmentFootprint/tces}>), the filter matches
        if **any** element in the array satisfies the filter condition;
    3. Host systems CAN support any depth of nesting.

    <div class="example">
        To filter <{ShipmentFootprint|ShipmentFootprints}> by the origin location of their embedded TCEs:
        ```
        tces.origin.city=Rotterdam
        ```
        This returns all <{ShipmentFootprint|ShipmentFootprints}> containing at least one <{TCE}>
        whose <{TCE/origin}> has a matching city.
    </div>

    For all properties with timestamp or numerical values, filtering SHOULD support the possibility of specifying a range of values, implemented as follows:

      1. The `$name` of the filter pair is the name of the timestamp or numerical property (e.g., `createdAt`).
      1. The `$name` should be followed by either the operator `=gte.` (greater than or equal) or `=lt.` (less than).
      1. The `$value` of the filter pair is either numerical (integer or [=Decimal=]) or a date and time string conforming to ISO 8601 with timezone UTC.
      1. To filter within the range defined by a start value and an end value, two filter pairs need to be concatenated with `&`.

    <div class="example">
        To filter <{ShipmentFootprint|ShipmentFootprints}> by the creation time between 2025-01-01 (inclusive) and 2026-01-01 (exclusive):
        ```
        createdAt=gte.2025-01-01T00:00:00Z&createdAt=lt.2026-01-01T00:00:00Z
        ```
        This returns all <{ShipmentFootprint|ShipmentFootprints}> created on or after `2025-01-01T00:00:00Z` and before `2026-01-01T00:00:00Z`.
    </div>


: <dfn>Limit</dfn>
::
    `Limit` is an OPTIONAL request parameter. If defined,
      1. the name of the HTTP request parameter MUST be `limit` and
      2. the value MUST be a positive integer.

: <dfn>StatusCode</dfn>
::
    If the host system returns transport activity data, the `HttpStatusCode` MUST be 200.

    If the host system responds with an error response, the `HttpStatusCode` MUST match the HTTP Status Code of the respective error response code, as defined in the [PACT Technical Specifications](https://wbcsd.github.io/tr/2023/data-exchange-protocol-20231207/#api-error-responsesm).

: <dfn>StatusText</dfn>
::
    The HTTP Status text conforming to the HTTP status code [=StatusCode=].

: <dfn>ResponseBody</dfn>
::
    The HTTP response body upon a successful request. The body MUST be a JSON object with property `data` with value the
    list of the respective data (<{ShipmentFootprint}> for [[#action-sd|Action ShipmentFootprintData]], <{TOC}> for [[#action-tocd|Action TOC]], etc. ). The list MUST be encoded as
    a JSON array.

    If the host system does not accept the access token, the body MUST be an error response with code [AccessDenied](https://wbcsd.github.io/tr/2024/data-exchange-protocol-20240410/#accessdenied).

    If the host system does not accept the access token because it expired, the body SHOULD be an error response with code [TokenExpired](https://wbcsd.github.io/tr/2024/data-exchange-protocol-20240410/#tokenexpired).

    In all other cases, for instance in case of a malformed value of the header authorization, the body SHOULD be an error response with code [BadRequest](https://wbcsd.github.io/tr/2024/data-exchange-protocol-20240410/#badrequest).

: <dfn>ContentLength</dfn>
:: The length of the body. See [[!rfc9112]].

: <dfn>PaginationLink</dfn>
:: See [=pagination link=] and [[#pagination]].

: <dfn>AuthEndpoint</dfn>
::
    The endpoint to request an [=access token=]. See [[#authentication]] for further details on discovery and request syntax.


## Authentication ## {#authentication}

Issue: Needs revision. In particular, we need to consider not demanding BasicAuth implementation with client credentials.

With the deprecation of PACT interoperability, iLEAP defines an [=authentication flow=] for the
[=iLEAP standalone API=]. An [=access token=] obtained through either authentication method ([=PACT-based API|PACT=] or [=iLEAP standalone API=])
MUST be valid for both [=PACT-based API|PACT-based=] and [=iLEAP standalone API=] endpoints.

### Authentication Flow ### {#auth-flow}

The iLEAP <dfn>authentication flow</dfn> consists of the following steps:

1. Token endpoint discovery, as specified in [[#auth-endpoint-discovery]].
1. Authentication against the token endpoint, as specified in [[#action-authenticate]].

Note:
  The iLEAP [=authentication flow=] follows the approach of [[!PACTDX]], Section 7.3.
  This means that [=host systems=] implementing the PACT-based authentication flow are
  also conforming with the iLEAP authentication flow.


### AuthEndpoint Discovery ### {#auth-endpoint-discovery}

A [=host system=] MAY use any endpoint for authentication, as long as they make it available through
an OpenId Configuration Document. In order to discover the authentication endpoint, a [=data recipient=] MUST:
1. retrieve and validate the [=OpenId Provider Configuration Document=] of the host system (see
    [[!OPENID-CONNECT]]) from the endpoint
    `https://`[=Hostname=]`/`[=Subpath=]`/.well-known/openid-configuration`;
1. use as [=AuthEndpoint=] the value of the `token_endpoint` property of the
    [=OpenId Provider Configuration Document=].

If the [=host system=] does not provide a valid OpenId Configuration Document at the above endpoint
or that the `token_endpoint` is not defined, the [=data recipient=] MUST use
[=Hostname=]`/`[=Subpath=]`/auth/token` as the [=AuthEndpoint=].


## Action Authenticate ## {#action-authenticate}

Request an access token using client credentials.

[=Host systems=] MUST implement this action in conformance with [[!rfc6749]] Section 4.4 (OAuth2 Client Credentials).

[=Host systems=] MAY offer this action under any [=AuthEndpoint=], discoverable as per [[#auth-endpoint-discovery]].
Accordingly, if no discovery method through an OpenId Configuration Document is implemented, the [=host system=] MUST
offer this action under the endpoint [=Hostname=]`/`[=Subpath=]`/auth/token`.

### Request Syntax ### {#action-authenticate-request}

<pre highlight=http>
POST <l>[=AuthEndpoint=]</l> HTTP/1.1
accept: application/json
content-type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
authorization: Basic <l>[=BasicAuth=]</l>
content-length: <l>[=ContentLength=]</l>

<l>[=AuthBody=]</l>
</pre>

With Request parameters:

: <dfn>BasicAuth</dfn>
:: See [[!rfc6749]] Section 4.4.2

: <dfn>AuthBody</dfn>
:: See [[!rfc6749]] Section 4.4

#### Example #### {#example-authenticate-request}

<div class=example>
  Request an access token using client credentials:

  ```http
  POST https://api.ileap.sine.dev/auth/token HTTP/1.1
  accept: application/json
  content-type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
  authorization: Basic Q2xpZW50SUQ6Q2xpZW50U2VjcmV0
  content-length: 29
  grant_type=client_credentials
  ```
</div>

  Authentication flow identical to [[!PACTDX]] (see Chapter 7.3).

### Response Syntax ### {#action-authenticate-response}

<pre highlight=http>
HTTP/1.1 <l>[=AuthStatusCode=]</l> OK
content-type: application/json
content-length: <l>[=ContentLength=]</l>

<l>[=AuthResponseBody=]</l>
</pre>

With action-specific response parameters

: <dfn>AuthStatusCode</dfn>
:: A HTTP response code conforming to [[!rfc6749]] Section 4.4 and Section 5.

: <dfn>AuthResponseBody</dfn>
:: A JSON Object conforming to either [[!rfc6749]] Section 4.4 in case
    of successful authentication (containing an [=access token=]), or [[!rfc6749]] Section 5.2
    otherwise.

#### Example #### {#example-authenticate-response}

<div class=example>
  Example of a successful response containing an access token:

  ```http
  HTTP/1.1 200 OK
  content-type: application/json
  content-length: 123

  {
    "access_token": "eyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...",
    "token_type": "Bearer",
    "expires_in": 3600
  }
  ```
</div>

## Common HTTP Endpoint Behaviors ## {#http-rest-api-common-behaviors}

The specifications, behaviors, and considerations of this subchapter apply to all [=iLEAP standalone API=] actions except for [[#action-authenticate]].


### Access Control ### {#access-control}

A [=host system=] MUST implement an access control mechanism such that each API response
contains only data intended for the requesting [=data recipient=].

This applies to all [=iLEAP standalone API=] actions except for [[#action-authenticate|Action Authenticate]].

The mechanism by which a [=host system=] determines which data is intended for a given
[=data recipient=] is implementation-specific.


### Filtering ### {#filtering}

Filtering CAN be requested by a [=data recipient=] by supplying a [=filter statement=] through the [=Filter=] request parameter.


If a [=host system=] does not implement filtering, it MUST process the request as if no [=Filter=] was provided.

If a [=host system=] implements filtering, it SHOULD process the filter statement on a best-effort basis:

1. it CAN ignore the filter statement or parts of the filter statement, or
1. it CAN return an error response as defined in the [=ResponseBody=]. For instance, a host system CAN return an HTTP
    error code `400` and a body with error `NotImplemented` if it does not support a specific filter pair;
1. it CAN treat concatenated filters disjunctively, i.e., returning the union of the results of the individual filters.

### Pagination ### {#pagination}

Support for pagination is REQUIRED for [=host systems=] and [=data recipients=].

[=Host systems=] MUST implement pagination server-side, such that

1. the host system MAY return less data than requested through the [=Limit=] request parameter;
1. the host system MUST return a `Link` header if there is additional data ready to be retrieved, such that
    1. the `Link` header conforms to [[!RFC8288]];
    1. the value of the `rel` parameter is equal to `next`;
    1. the target IRI (RFC8288, section 3.1) of the `Link` header is absolute;
    1. the value of `host` of the target IRI is equal to the value of the `host` request header from
        the original HTTP request.

The target IRI from a pagination `link` header is called a <dfn>pagination link</dfn>.

Upon a [=host system=] returning a [=pagination link=]:

1. a data recipient CAN call the pagination link more than once;
1. upon each call, the host system;
    1. MUST return the same data from the same pagination link, upon successful authentication (see [[#authentication]]);
    1. MUST NOT return more data than requested in case [=Limit=] was defined by a [=data recipient=];
    1. MUST return a second `Link` header conforming with the previous description in case there is
        additional data  available;
1. if a response contains a second pagination link, upon the data recipient calling the second
    pagination link, the previous pagination link MAY no longer work.
    - i.e. data recipients MUST NOT assume that previous pagination links continue to return results
        after advancing in the pagination process;
1. a pagination link MUST be valid for at least 180 seconds after creation;
1. a data recipient SHOULD retry calling the pagination link after the server returned an error, and
    SHOULD use a randomized exponential back-off strategy when retrying.

A [=data recipient=] CAN trigger pagination by supplying a [=Limit=] request parameter.

Irrespective of whether a [=Limit=] parameter is supplied, a [=data recipient=] SHOULD
be able to process paginated responses, such that it is able
1. to process responses containing a pagination link, and
1. to call pagination links until no more pagination link are
    provided by the host system.

[=Data recipients=] SHOULD implement a strategy to deal with pagination links no
longer working, including retrying (using appropriate back-off strategies etc.),
or completely re-starting the data retrieval process from the beginning.


## Action ShipmentFootprintData ## {#action-sd}

Lists the [=data owner=]'s <{ShipmentFootprint|ShipmentFootprints}> with REQUIRED [[#access-control]], REQUIRED [[#pagination]], and OPTIONAL [[#filtering]].

Note:
  To retrieve <{ShipmentFootprint|ShipmentFootprints}> based on embedded properties (regardless of the level of nesting),
  [=data recipients=] SHOULD use [[#filtering]]. See [[#action-sd-request-examples]] for examples.

### Request Syntax ### {#action-sd-request}

<pre highlight=http>
  GET <l>[=Subpath=]</l>/v1/ileap/shipments?<l>[=Filter=]</l>&<l>[=Limit=]</l> HTTP/1.1
  host: <l>[=Hostname=]</l>
  authorization: Bearer <l>[=BearerToken=]</l>
</pre>

#### Examples #### {#action-sd-request-examples}

To retrieve all `ShipmentFootprints`, the [=data recipient=] can call the endpoint as follows:

<div class=example>
  ```http
  GET /v1/ileap/shipments HTTP/1.1
  ```
</div>

To retrieve the `ShipmentFootprint` for the shipment with <{ShipmentFootprint/shipmentId}> equal to `47389557`,
the [=data recipient=] can use the [=Filter=] parameter with filter pair `shipmentId=$shipmentId` as follows:

<div class=example>
  ```http
  GET /v1/ileap/shipments?shipmentId=47389557 HTTP/1.1
  ```
</div>

To get `ShipmentFootprints` where at least one TCE has <{TCE/tceId}> equal to `"40t-diesel-2023"`:

<div class=example>
  ```http
  GET /v1/ileap/shipments?tces.tceId=40t-diesel-2023 HTTP/1.1
  ```
</div>

To filter for `ShipmentFootprints` where at least one TCE has the origin <{Location/city}> equal to `"Berlin"`:

<div class=example>

  ```http
  GET /v1/ileap/shipments?tces.origin.city=berlin HTTP/1.1
  ```
</div>

### Response Syntax ### {#action-sd-response}

Non-paginated response:

<pre highlight=http>
  HTTP/1.1 <l>[=StatusCode=]</l> <l>[=StatusText=]</l>
  Content-Type: application/json
  Content-Length: <l>[=ContentLength=]</l>

  <l>[=ResponseBody=]</l>
</pre>

Paginated response ([[#pagination]]):

<pre highlight=http>
  HTTP/1.1 <l>[=StatusCode=]</l> <l>[=StatusText=]</l>
  Content-Type: application/json
  Content-Length: <l>[=ContentLength=]</l>
  Link: <l>[=PaginationLink=]</l>; rel="next"

  <l>[=ResponseBody=]</l>
</pre>

#### Examples #### {#action-sd-response-examples}

Issue: example needs revision

<div class=example>
  Example response to request with `limit=1`

  ```http
  HTTP/1.1 200 OK
  Content-Type: application/json
  Content-Length: 512
  Link: <https://api.ileap.sine.dev/v1/ileap/shipments?limit=1&offset=1>; rel="next"

  {
    "data": [
      {
        "shipmentId": "shipment-1",
        "companyName": "Acme Logistics",
        "referencePeriodStart": "2025-01-01T00:00:00Z",
        "referencePeriodEnd": "2026-01-01T00:00:00Z",
        "dataSchema": "https://api.ileap.sine.dev/shipment-footprint.json",
        "documentation": "https://sine-fdn.github.io/ileap-extension/",
        "productCategoryCpc": "83117",
        "mass": "1000",
        "tces": [
          {
            "tceId": "40t-diesel-2023",
            "shipentId": "shipment-1",
            "tocId": "40t-diesel-2023",
            "origin": {
              "country": "NL",
              "city": "Rotterdam"
            },
            "destination": {
              "country": "DE",
              "city": "Berlin"
            },
            "mass": "1000",
            "distance": {
              "actual": "800",
            },
            "transportActivity": "800000",
            "co2eWTW": "200",
            "co2eTTW": "150",
          }
        ]
      },
    ]
  }
  ```
</div>

## Action TOCData ## {#action-tocd}

Lists the [=data owner=]'s <{TOC|TOCs}> with REQUIRED [[#access-control]], REQUIRED [[#pagination]], and OPTIONAL [[#filtering]].

Note:
  To retrieve TOCs based on embedded properties (regardless of the level of nesting),
  [=data recipients=] SHOULD use [[#filtering]]. See [[#action-tocd-request-examples]] for examples.


### Request Syntax ### {#action-tocd-request}

<pre highlight=http>
  GET <l>[=Subpath=]</l>/v1/ileap/tocs?<l>[=Filter=]</l>&<l>[=Limit=]</l> HTTP/1.1
  host: <l>[=Hostname=]</l>
  authorization: Bearer <l>[=BearerToken=]</l>
</pre>

#### Examples #### {#action-tocd-request-examples}

<div class=example>
  Get all `TOCs`

  ```http
  GET /v1/ileap/tocs HTTP/1.1
  ```
</div>

To retrieve only one TOC, identified by <{TOC/tocId}> equal to `"40t-diesel-2023"`:

<div class=example>
  ```http
  GET /v1/ileap/tocs?tocId=40t-diesel-2023 HTTP/1.1
  ```
</div>

To retrieve <{TOC|TOCs}> where at least one of their <{TOC/energyCarriers}> has <{EnergyCarrier/energyCarrier}> equal to `"Diesel"`:

<div class=example>
  ```http
  GET /v1/ileap/tocs?energyCarriers.energyCarrier=diesel HTTP/1.1
  ```
</div>

To filter for `TOCs` where the <{TOC/energyCarriers}> include <{EnergyCarrier|EnergyCarriers}> with <{Feedstock/feedstock}> `"Fossil"`

<div class=example>
  ```http
  GET /v1/ileap/tocs?energyCarriers.feedstocks.feedstock=fossil HTTP/1.1
  ```
</div>

### Response Syntax ### {#action-tocd-response}

Non-paginated response:

<pre highlight=http>
  HTTP/1.1 <l>[=StatusCode=]</l> <l>[=StatusText=]</l>
  Content-Type: application/json
  Content-Length: <l>[=ContentLength=]</l>

  <l>[=ResponseBody=]</l>
</pre>

Paginated response ([[#pagination]]):

<pre highlight=http>
  HTTP/1.1 <l>[=StatusCode=]</l> <l>[=StatusText=]</l>
  Content-Type: application/json
  Content-Length: <l>[=ContentLength=]</l>
  Link: <l>[=PaginationLink=]</l>; rel="next"

  <l>[=ResponseBody=]</l>
</pre>

#### Examples #### {#action-tocd-response-examples}

Issue: example needs revision

<div class=example>
  Example response to request with `limit=1`

  ```http
  HTTP/1.1 200 OK
  Content-Type: application/json
  Content-Length: 512
  Link: <https://api.ileap.sine.dev/v1/ileap/tocs?limit=1&offset=1>; rel="next"

  {
    "data": [
      {
        "tocId": "40t-diesel-2023",
        "companyName": "Acme Logistics",
        "referencePeriodStart": "2025-01-01T00:00:00Z",
        "referencePeriodEnd": "2026-01-01T00:00:00Z",
        "dataSchema": "https://api.ileap.sine.dev/shipment-footprint.json",
        "documentation": "https://sine-fdn.github.io/ileap-extension/",
        "productCategoryCpc": "83117",
        "mode": "Road",
        "energyCarriers": [
          {
            "energyCarrier": "Diesel",
            "relativeShare": "1.0",
          }
        ],
        "co2eIntensityWTW": "0.25",
        "co2eIntensityTTW": "0.2",
        "transportActivityUnit": "tkm"
      }
    ]
  }
  ```
</div>

## Action HOCData ## {#action-hocd}

Lists the [=data owner=]'s <{HOC|HOCs}> with REQUIRED [[#access-control]], REQUIRED [[#pagination]], and OPTIONAL [[#filtering]].

Note:
  To retrieve HOCs based on embedded properties (regardless of the level of nesting),
  [=data recipients=] SHOULD use [[#filtering]]. See [[#action-hocd-request-examples]] for examples.


### Request Syntax ### {#action-hocd-request}

<pre highlight=http>
  GET <l>[=Subpath=]</l>/v1/ileap/hocs?<l>[=Filter=]</l>&<l>[=Limit=]</l> HTTP/1.1
  host: <l>[=Hostname=]</l>
  authorization: Bearer <l>[=BearerToken=]</l>
</pre>

#### Examples #### {#action-hocd-request-examples}

To retrieve all `HOCs`:

<div class=example>
  ```http
  GET /v1/ileap/hocs HTTP/1.1
  ```
</div>

To retrieve the `HOC` identified by <{HOC/hocId}> equal to `"hub-rotterdam"`:

<div class=example>

  ```http
  GET /v1/ileap/hocs?hocId=hub-rotterdam HTTP/1.1
  ```
</div>

To filter for `HOCs` where the <{HOC/energyCarriers}> include <{EnergyCarrier|EnergyCarriers}> with <{Feedstock/feedstock}> `"Fossil"`

<div class=example>
  ```http
  GET /v1/ileap/hocs?energyCarriers.feedstocks.feedstock=fossil HTTP/1.1
  ```
</div>

To filter for `HOCs` where the <{HOC/hubLocation}> has <{Location/city}> equal to `"Hamburg"`

<div class=example>
  ```http
  GET /v1/ileap/hocs?hubLocation.city=hamburg HTTP/1.1
  ```
</div>

### Response Syntax ### {#action-hocd-response}

Non-paginated response:

<pre highlight=http>
  HTTP/1.1 <l>[=StatusCode=]</l> <l>[=StatusText=]</l>
  Content-Type: application/json
  Content-Length: <l>[=ContentLength=]</l>

  <l>[=ResponseBody=]</l>
</pre>

Paginated response ([[#pagination]]):

<pre highlight=http>
  HTTP/1.1 <l>[=StatusCode=]</l> <l>[=StatusText=]</l>
  Content-Type: application/json
  Content-Length: <l>[=ContentLength=]</l>
  Link: <l>[=PaginationLink=]</l>; rel="next"

  <l>[=ResponseBody=]</l>
</pre>

#### Examples #### {#action-hocd-response-examples}

Issue: example needs revision

<div class=example>
  Example response to request with `limit=1`

  ```http
  HTTP/1.1 200 OK
  Content-Type: application/json
  Content-Length: 512
  Link: <https://api.ileap.sine.dev/v1/ileap/hocs?limit=1&offset=1>; rel="next"

  {
    "data": [
      {
        "hocId": "hub-rotterdam",
        "companyName": "Acme Logistics",
        "referencePeriodStart": "2025-01-01T00:00:00Z",
        "referencePeriodEnd": "2026-01-01T00:00:00Z",
        "dataSchema": "https://api.ileap.sine.dev/shipment-footprint.json",
        "documentation": "https://sine-fdn.github.io/ileap-extension/",
        "productCategoryCpc": "83117",
        "hubType": "Transshipment",
        "energyCarriers": [
          {
            "energyCarrier": "Electricity",
            "relativeShare": "1.0",
          }
        ],
        "co2eIntensityWTW": "0.5",
        "co2eIntensityTTW": "0.1",
        "hubActivityUnit": "tonnes"
      }
    ]
  }
  ```
</div>

## Action TransportActivityData ## {#action-tad}

Lists the [=data owner=]'s [=Transport Activity Data=] with REQUIRED [[#access-control]], REQUIRED [[#pagination]], and OPTIONAL [[#filtering]].

Note:
  To retrieve `TransportActivityData` based on embedded properties (regardless of the level of nesting),
  [=data recipients=] SHOULD use [[#filtering]]. See [[#action-tad-request-examples]] for examples.

### Request Syntax ### {#action-tad-request}

Advisement: As part of the deprecation of PACT interoperability, the version of the iLEAP native
endpoints has been changed from `/2/ileap/` to `/v1/ileap/`. However, to maintain backward
compatibility with existing implementations, a [=host system=] MUST support both versions of the
endpoint. Below, only the new version is documented.

<pre highlight=http>
  GET <l>[=Subpath=]</l>/v1/ileap/tad?<l>[=Filter=]</l>&<l>[=Limit=]</l> HTTP/1.1
  host: <l>[=Hostname=]</l>
  authorization: Bearer <l>[=BearerToken=]</l>
</pre>

#### Examples #### {#action-tad-request-examples}

To retrieve all `TransportActivityData`:

<div class=example>
  ```http
  GET /v1/ileap/tad HTTP/1.1
  ```
</div>

To get the `TransportActivity` with <{TAD/activityId}> equal to `"123456"`:

<div class=example>

  ```http
  GET /v1/ileap/tad?activityId=123456 HTTP/1.1
  ```
</div>

To filter for `TransportActivityData` where the <{TAD/energyCarriers}> include <{EnergyCarrier|EnergyCarriers}> with <{Feedstock/feedstock}> `"Fossil"`:

<div class=example>

  ```http
  GET /v1/ileap/tad?energyCarriers.feedstocks.feedstock=fossil HTTP/1.1
  ```
</div>

To retrieve `TransportActivityData` with [=Feedstock=] equal to `"Fossil"` and with <{TAD/packagingOrTrEqType}> equal to `"Pallet"`:

<div class=example>

  ```http
  GET /v1/ileap/tad?feedstock=Fossil&packagingOrTrEqType=pallet HTTP/1.1
  ```
</div>

### Response Syntax ### {#action-tad-response}

Non-paginated response:

<pre highlight=http>
  HTTP/1.1 <l>[=StatusCode=]</l> <l>[=StatusText=]</l>
  content-type: application/json
  content-length: <l>[=ContentLength=]</l>

  <l>[=ResponseBody=]</l>
</pre>

Paginated response ([[#pagination]]):

<pre highlight=http>
  HTTP/1.1 <l>[=StatusCode=]</l> <l>[=StatusText=]</l>
  content-type: application/json
  content-length: <l>[=ContentLength=]</l>
  link: <l>[=PaginationLink=]</l>; rel="next"

  <l>[=ResponseBody=]</l>
</pre>

#### Example #### {#action-tad-response-examples}

<div class=example>
  Example response to request with `limit=1`

  ```http
  HTTP/1.1 200 OK
  content-type: application/json
  content-length: 1321
  link: <https://api.ileap.sine.dev/v1/ileap/tad?offset=1&limit=1>; rel="next"
  ```

  ```json
  {
    "data": [
      {
        "activityId": "1",
        "consignmentIds": [
          "1"
        ],
        "distance": {
          "actual": "656.0"
        },
        "mass": "1000.0",
        "loadFactor": "0.8",
        "emptyDistanceFactor": "0.1",
        "origin": {
