## Bilateral Testing ## {#conformity-bilateral-testing}

A Bilateral Test is an interoperability test where two different [=host system=]
implementations participate to verify conformance ([[#conformance]]) and their
ability to work together.

One system acts as the [=data owner=]. It is called the <dfn>target host system</dfn> and is the system under test.
The second system acts as the testing party.

Note:
  The objective of Bilateral Testing is to ensure that systems can effectively
  communicate despite having independent codebases.


## Submission ## {#conformity-submission}

Note: non-normative

Once a [=host system=] achieved [=iLEAP conformance=] in 1 or all kinds of iLEAP conformance,
the implementer is requested to reach out to the authors of these Technical Specifications to
apply for additional support, materials, and marketing opportunities.


# Appendix A: Changelog # {#changelog}


## Version 1.1.0-20260326 ## {#version-1.1.0-20260326}

First draft release of Version 1.1.0, containing the following changes:
- addition of new data transaction 4 ([[#txn4]]) and corresponding data type ([[#dt-ar]])
- addition of [=iLEAP standalone protocol=] and [=iLEAP standalone api=] ([[#http-rest-api]])
    - including common behavior specified in [[#http-rest-api-common-behaviors]]
- deprecation of PACT technical interoperability (see [[#pact-interop]] and [=PACT-based API=])
- updated definitions
- updated introductions for data types <{ShipmentFootprint}> and <{TAD}>
- fixed references to PACT Technical Specifications v2.2
- improvements of the PACT Integration Chapter [[#pcf-mapping]]
- addition of optional <{TAD/specVersion|TAD/specVersion}>
- addition of new endpoint for [[#txn3]] aligned with the iLEAP standalone protocol
- addition of new test cases for iLEAP standalone protocol in [[#ileap-conformance-matrix]]
- updated [[#test-case-027]] (formerly TC007) to accept 401 Unauthorized in addition to 403 Forbidden
- remove references to SI units
- use 'backward compatibility' instad of 'backwards compatibility' for consistency


